W.","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"5 years ago","ctime":"August 5 2011, 04:32:18 UTC","massactions":0,"subject":"","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://sephen.livejournal.com/","striked":1,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"sephen","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"sephen","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://sephen.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"sephen","ctime_ts":1312518738,"tracked":0},{"shown":1,"collapsed":0,"userpic":"http://l-userpic.livejournal.com/125422321/25658039","actions":[{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14414507#t14414507","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14414507#t14414507","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14414507#t14414507","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"comalies","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://comalies.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":14414507,"talkid":56306,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14414507#t14414507","above":14410923,"upictitle":"Nicolas Cage Enthusiast: Ciri 2","article":"DON'T APOLOGIZE, CAPS LOCK MAKES EVERYTHING 1000X BETTER!","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"5 years ago","ctime":"August 5 2011, 19:19:59 UTC","parent":14410923,"massactions":0,"subject":"","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://comalies.livejournal.com/","striked":null,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/user_ontd.gif?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"comalies","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"comalies","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://comalies.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"comalies","ctime_ts":1312571999,"tracked":0},{"shown":1,"collapsed":0,"actions":[{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14411179#t14411179","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14411179#t14411179","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14411179#t14411179","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"mr_jacobean","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://mr-jacobean.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":14411179,"talkid":56293,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14411179#t14411179","upictitle":"mr_jacobean: pic#111509615","article":"Here's my summary (not the most concise one, I admit ^^) of what's in the interview.<br /><br />The interview begins with George expressing his pleasure at having been chosen by “Time” as one of the world’s 100 most influential people in  2011. He believes it is a mark of fantasy literature being finally recognized as a part of the US mainstream culture.  He then proceeds to discuss the gradual disappearance of the conventional boundary between fantasy and mainstream literature, observable both in the number of mainstream authors who tend to employ motifs typical of fantasy or sci-fi and in the increasing numbers of works representing the said genres being reviewed in various prestigious publications. George says that, after all, all such divisions are artificial: what counts is a story. You might have a book with a poor plot or a book with a most riveting storyline; the genre does not determine the novel’s quality in any way. Any such presumption is, these days, rather old-fashioned and lacking in substance. The third question concerns  different literary prizes and the joyful fact that fantasy and sci-fi works have recently been shortlisted for the most prestigious prizes (the ones that are not, at least judging by their names, genre-bound: the Nobel prize, the Pulitzer prize.)<br /><br />The interview then moves to ASoIaF. There is a discussion of a perfect balance between realism and mythology/magic that should characterize a fantasy novel. Too much magic or too many prophesies might upstage the characters, make the plot progress artificially (e.g. leading to deus ex machina solutions.) George believes that the essence of literature are the characters and their decisions, struggles. Magic should only be a tool, and a rather unhandy, even unwanted, one. And that’s what might be encountered also in “The Lord of the Rings”: there isn’t really much magic in Tolkien’s world, the characters must depend on their own efforts (thus, this is undoubtedly the tradition George's own works follow.) <br /><br />Later on, the interview discusses the way in which the HBO show complements the books (e.g. the deeper insight into Robert and Cersei’s marriage.) Goerge stresses the fact that books and television productions represent different media; hence, they should always be judged separately, never by means of comparing one to the other. <br /><br />The interview also touches upon the fact that it was ASoIaF that made many people want to read some other novels representing the fantasy genre; George points out, though, that he knows many individuals who love his books but still are not interested in the genre as a whole.<br /><br />Next, there is a question about the tricky art of inventing names for one's characters. George says he wanted to avoid the problem that often besets many fantasy novels: names that are hard to pronounce. Therefore, he employed the technique of modifying the actual English names. What is more, George also admits that he flouted a rule which says that in fantasy you shouldn’t have two characters whose names start with the same letter (so as not to make the reader confused.) He says he didn't do so in ASoIaF because of historical novels he loves reading, and we all know that in history there were many Edwards and Henrys etc. Thus, we have numerous Lannisters whose names begin with “Ty-“. <br /><br />The influence of historical novels upon George’s writing is indisputable: George likes fantasy which is flavored with history. But it is the strength of a story set in an alternative world that you don’t know its ending (which is not so easy to achieve in historical fiction, clearly.)<br /><br />Finally, the interview talks about the killing of the characters (pointing to the HBO viewers’ shock at Ned’s beheading) and ends with the conclusion that “no one wants to be in the prologue,” as most characters that have their POVs there die.<br />","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"5 years ago","ctime":"August 5 2011, 07:37:48 UTC","massactions":0,"subject":"Summary of the interview","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://mr-jacobean.livejournal.com/","striked":1,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"mr_jacobean","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"mr_jacobean","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://mr-jacobean.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"mr_jacobean","ctime_ts":1312529868,"tracked":0},{"shown":1,"collapsed":0,"actions":[{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14412971#t14412971","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14412971#t14412971","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14412971#t14412971","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"dp68","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://dp68.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":14412971,"talkid":56300,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14412971#t14412971","upictitle":"dp68: pic#0","article":"You have to love Google Translation:<br /><br />Q:  It is time to confidently go to the \"Song of Ice and Fire.\" It seems to me that readers are saying about this cycle, mainly as a work of realistic, low fantasy. But it also has another page, through which resembles epic: with symbols, prophecies, the general development of the plot, a reference to Celtic mythology and the like. How important is, you think, this second novel aspect of the Lord?","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"5 years ago","ctime":"August 5 2011, 13:01:29 UTC","massactions":0,"subject":"Google Translation","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://dp68.livejournal.com/","striked":1,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"dp68","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"dp68","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://dp68.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"dp68","ctime_ts":1312549289,"tracked":0},{"shown":1,"collapsed":0,"actions":[{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14413483#t14413483","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14413483#t14413483","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14413483#t14413483","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"ext_733350","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://rrrgroup.blogspot.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":14413483,"talkid":56302,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/230827.html?thread=14413483#t14413483","upictitle":"rrrgroup.blogspot.com: pic#0","article":"A \"nice\" review of A Dance with Dragons and als